🔷 Automated Engineering Drawing Compliance Checker

Problem Overview

Engineering drawings must adhere to strict standards to ensure manufacturability and correctness. Current verification processes are largely manual, making them time-intensive, error-prone, and difficult to scale. This work aims to develop a fully automated drawing checker that evaluates engineering drawings against a predefined checklist and provides both compliance status and corrective feedback.

⸻

Methodology Overview

The proposed system follows a structured pipeline that begins with information extraction from engineering drawings (PDF/DXF formats), followed by rule-based validation and feedback generation. Initially, drawings are processed to identify distinct views and detect annotations such as dimensions and symbols using a deep learning–based approach (YOLOv8). To further interpret geometric content, the extracted views are preprocessed through skeletonization and stroke analysis, and curves are approximated using cubic Bézier fitting to obtain vectorized representations.

The extracted geometric and annotation data are then passed to a checklist-driven rule engine, which encodes engineering standards and evaluates the drawing for compliance. The system finally outputs a structured result indicating whether each criterion is satisfied, along with detailed feedback highlighting missing or incorrect elements.

⸻

Challenges and Design Exploration

A key challenge encountered throughout this work is achieving reliable and semantically consistent extraction from diverse drawing formats.

The image-based pipeline, combining view detection, annotation detection, and vectorization, offers flexibility but suffers from loss of geometric fidelity, leading to ambiguity in distinguishing features such as lines and arcs. This makes it unsuitable for precise validation tasks.

An alternative OCR-based document parsing approach was explored using Docling with RapidOCR. While effective for textual extraction, it fails to robustly identify drawing structure and views, limiting its applicability for engineering diagrams.

To address geometric inaccuracies, a DXF-based approach using the ezdxf library was implemented. This method successfully extracts geometric entities with high precision; however, it introduces a critical limitation — the absence of associativity between features, views, and annotations. Attempts to resolve this through clustering-based techniques did not yield reliable results.

⸻

Key Limitation

The central bottleneck identified is not merely feature extraction, but the lack of semantic linkage between geometric elements, views, and annotations. This associativity is essential for meaningful checklist validation and remains an open challenge.

⸻

Current Status and Conclusion

While a functional checklist evaluation engine has been successfully developed, the overall system is constrained by limitations in extraction reliability and semantic understanding across varied drawing inputs. Existing approaches present a trade-off between geometric accuracy and contextual interpretability, preventing robust end-to-end automation.

This work highlights that the next step toward a fully automated solution lies in developing a hybrid framework that combines precise geometric extraction with context-aware association mechanisms, enabling accurate and scalable engineering drawing validation.

