🔷 Automated Engineering Drawing Compliance Checker

🧩 Problem Statement

Engineering drawings are critical for manufacturing and design validation. However, manual verification against standards and checklists is:
	•	Time-consuming
	•	Error-prone
	•	Not scalable across large datasets

👉 Objective:
Develop a fully automated system that:
	•	Extracts information from engineering drawings (PDF/DXF)
	•	Validates them against a predefined checklist
	•	Outputs:
	•	✅ Compliance status (Satisfied / Not Satisfied)
	•	⚠️ Detailed feedback for corrections

⸻

⚙️ Proposed Methodology (Pipeline Overview)

Input: Engineering Drawing (PDF / DXF)

Step 1: Information Extraction
	•	View Detection → Identify orthographic views from drawings
	•	Annotation Detection → Detect dimensions, symbols, and text using YOLOv8
	•	Feature Extraction (Vectorization):
	•	Skeletonization of drawing
	•	Stroke detection
	•	Curve fitting using Cubic Bézier curves

⸻

Step 2: Rule-Based Evaluation Engine
	•	Encodes engineering checklist rules
	•	Maps extracted features + annotations
	•	Performs compliance validation

⸻

Step 3: Feedback Generation
	•	Binary result: Pass / Fail
	•	Detailed feedback:
	•	Missing annotations
	•	Incorrect dimensions
	•	Violations of standards

⸻

⚠️ Challenges & Attempted Solutions

🔍 1. Image-Based Extraction Pipeline

Approach:
	•	View detection + YOLOv8 annotation detection
	•	Vectorization via skeletonization + Bézier fitting

Issue:
	•	❌ Loss of geometric fidelity
	•	❌ Feature ambiguity (lines/arcs misinterpreted)
	•	❌ No guarantee of exact reconstruction

⸻

📄 2. Document-Level Parsing (Docling + RapidOCR)

Approach:
	•	OCR-based extraction

Issue:
	•	❌ Poor view detection
	•	❌ Inconsistent structure recognition
	•	❌ Not suitable for complex engineering layouts

⸻

📐 3. DXF-Based Extraction (ezdxf)

Approach:
	•	Direct extraction of geometric entities (lines, arcs, circles)

Advantages:
	•	✅ High geometric accuracy
	•	✅ Reliable feature extraction

Issue:
	•	❌ No associativity:
	•	Features ↔ Views
	•	Features ↔ Annotations
	•	❌ Clustering-based mapping unreliable

⸻

🔗 4. Associativity Problem (Core Bottleneck)
	•	Difficulty linking:
	•	Geometry
	•	Views
	•	Annotations

👉 This is critical for checklist validation and remains unresolved.

⸻

🧠 Key Insight

Accurate feature extraction alone is insufficient —
semantic associativity between drawing components is essential.

⸻

📊 System Status
	•	✅ Checklist Rule Engine: Implemented and Functional
	•	⚠️ Extraction Pipeline: Partially Reliable
	•	❌ End-to-End Automation: Not yet robust

⸻

🧾 Conclusion
	•	A fully automated drawing checker requires:
	•	High-fidelity geometry extraction
	•	Robust view and annotation association
	•	Current approaches:
	•	Image-based → flexible but inaccurate
	•	DXF-based → accurate but lacks semantic linkage

👉 Future Direction:
	•	Hybrid pipeline:
	•	Combine DXF precision + ML-based semantic understanding
	•	Focus on:
	•	Graph-based association
	•	Context-aware feature linking

